                <head>114. Editorial Note</head>
                <p>On May 9, following the adjournment of the North Atlantic Council session, the
                    three Foreign Ministers reached agreement on the text of an invitation to the
                    Soviet Union to a Four-Power Conference. (<gloss target="#t_Dulte1"
                        >Dulte</gloss> 14 from Paris, May 9; Department of State, Central Files,
                    740.5/5–955) The text was approved by President <persName corresp="#p_EDD1"
                        >Eisenhower</persName> and Chancellor <persName corresp="#p_AK1"
                        >Adenauer</persName> on May 10 (<gloss target="#t_Tedul1">Tedul</gloss> 14
                    to Paris and <gloss target="#t_Dulte1">Dulte</gloss> 20 from Paris, May 10; <hi
                        rend="italic">ibid.,</hi> 396.1/5–955 and 5–1055), transmitted to the three
                    respective Embassies in the Soviet Union, and delivered to the Foreign Ministry
                    on the same day.</p>
                <p>For text of the note, which is the same in substance as the draft transmitted in
                        <ref target="#d108">Document 108</ref>, see Department of State <hi
                        rend="italic">Bulletin</hi>, May 23, 1955, pages 832–833.</p>
            </div>
        </body>
